SIMPLE: whiffle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whiffle
<hw>Whif"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Whiffled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Whiffling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>whiff</ets> to puff, perhaps influenced by D. <ets>weifelen</ets>
to waver.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To waver, or shake, as if moved by gusts of wind; to
shift, turn, or veer about.</def> <rj><au>D<?/mpier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To change from one opinion or course to another; to
use evasions; to prevaricate; to be fickle.</def><-- to waffle;
vacillate, equivocate, flip-flop. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A person of <qex>whiffing</qex> and unsteady turn of mind can not
keep close to a point of controversy.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiffle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whiffle
<hw>Whif"fle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To disperse with, or as with, a whiff, or puff; to
scatter.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dr. H. More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wave or shake quickly; to cause to
whiffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiffle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whiffle
<hw>Whif"fle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fife or small flute.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Douce.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiffler</ent>⟦br⟧
